<section xml:id="sec-combinations">
  <title>Combinations</title>

  <definition xml:id="def-combination">
    <title>Combination</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>combination</term> of items occurs when:
        <ul>
          <li><p>The items are selected from the same group.</p></li>
          <li><p>No item is used more than once.</p></li>
          <li><p><alert>The order of items makes no difference</alert>.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <exercise>
    <title>Distinguishing Permutations and Combinations</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each of the following, determine whether the problem involves permutations or combinations:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>How many ways can you select 6 free videos from a list of 200 videos?</p></li>
        <li><p>In a race with 50 runners and no ties, in how many ways can the first three finishers come in?</p></li>
        <li><p>Baskin-Robbins offers 31 flavors. How many different three-scoop bowls (each a different flavor) are possible?</p></li>
        <li><p>A three-person committee is needed from a board of six supervisors. How many different committees can be formed?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><term>Combination</term>: The order in which you pick the videos doesn't change the set you get to watch.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Permutation</term>: Order matters because 1st, 2nd, and 3rd place are different rankings.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Combination</term>: A bowl of Chocolate, Vanilla, and Strawberry is the same as Strawberry, Vanilla, and Chocolate.</p></li>
          <li><p><term>Combination</term>: On a committee, all members have equal status; the order of selection does not change the group's makeup.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <definition xml:id="def-combination-formula">
    <title>The Combination Formula</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The number of combinations of <m>n</m> things taken <m>r</m> at a time is denoted by <m>{}_n C_r</m>:
        <me>{}_n C_r = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!r!}</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <title>Public Transportation Committee</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A three-person committee is needed to study ways of improving public transportation. How many committees could be formed from the eight people on the board of supervisors?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since this is a committee where roles are not specified, the order does not matter. We use the combination formula with <m>n=8</m> and <m>r=3</m>:
        <me>{}_8 C_3 = \frac{8!}{(8-3)!3!} = \frac{8!}{5!3!}</me>
        Expanding the factorials:
        <me>\frac{8 \cdot 7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5!}{5! \cdot (3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1)} = \frac{336}{6} = 56</me>
        There are 56 possible committees.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>TI-30XIIS Keystrokes:</alert>
        Type <c>8</c> <m>\rightarrow</m> <c>PRB</c> <m>\rightarrow</m> Use arrow to underline <c>nCr</c> <m>\rightarrow</m> <c>ENTER</c> <m>\rightarrow</m> <c>3</c> <m>\rightarrow</m> <c>ENTER</c>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <title>The 107th Congress Committee</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The U.S. Senate of the 107th Congress consisted of 50 Democrats, 49 Republicans, and one independent. How many committees can be formed if each committee must have 3 Democrats and 2 Republicans?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We must choose the Democrats and the Republicans separately and then use the Fundamental Counting Principle to multiply them.
      </p>
      <p>
        Step 1: Choose 3 Democrats from 50:
        <me>{}_{50} C_3 = \frac{50 \cdot 49 \cdot 48}{3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1} = 19,600</me>
        Step 2: Choose 2 Republicans from 49:
        <me>{}_{49} C_2 = \frac{49 \cdot 48}{2 \cdot 1} = 1,176</me>
        Step 3: Multiply the results:
        <me>19,600 \cdot 1,176 = 23,049,600</me>
        There are 23,049,600 possible committees.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <title>Lottery Selections</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        To win a Mega Millions lottery, you must pick 5 numbers from a collection of 56, and one Megaball number from a collection of 46. The order of the first 5 numbers does not matter. How many different selections are possible?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        First, we calculate the combinations for the 5 numbers:
        <me>{}_{56} C_5 = \frac{56!}{51!5!} = 3,819,816</me>
        Next, there are 46 choices for the single Megaball. We multiply these together:
        <me>3,819,816 \cdot 46 = 175,711,536</me>
        There are over 175 million possible number combinations.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</section>
